# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: flameout
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:flameout/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:flameout/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:flameout/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:flameout/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:flameout/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:flameout/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:flameout/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:flameout/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:flameout/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:flameout/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:flameout/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:flameout/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:flameout/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:flameout/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:flameout/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:flameout/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:flameout/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:flameout/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:flameout/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:flameout/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:flameout/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:flameout/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:flameout/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:flameout/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:flameout/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:flameout/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:flameout/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:flameout/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:flameout/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:flameout/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:flameout/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:flameout/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:flameout/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:flameout/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:flameout/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:flameout/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:flameout/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:flameout/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:flameout/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:flameout/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:flameout/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:flameout/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:flameout/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] In an internal combustion engine or industrial furnace, the air–fuel ratio is an important measure for anti-pollution and performance-tuning reasons.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] If exactly enough air is provided to completely burn all of the fuel (**stoichiometric combustion**), the ratio is known as the **stoichiometric mixture**, often abbreviated to **stoich**.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios lower than stoichiometric (where the fuel is in excess) are considered "rich".
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Rich mixtures are less efficient, but may produce more power and burn cooler.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios higher than stoichiometric (where the air is in excess) are considered "lean".
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Lean mixtures are more efficient but may cause higher temperatures, which can lead to the formation of nitrogen oxides.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Some engines are designed with features to allow lean-burn.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] For precise air–fuel ratio calculations, the oxygen content of combustion air should be specified because of different air density due to different altitude or intake air temperature, possible dilution by ambient water vapor, or enrichment by oxygen additions.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] An **air-fuel ratio meter** monitors the air–fuel ratio of an internal combustion engine.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Also called **air–fuel ratio gauge**, **air–fuel meter**, or **air–fuel gauge**, it reads the voltage output of an oxygen sensor, sometimes also called **AFR sensor** or lambda sensor.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] The original narrow-band oxygen sensors became factory installed standard in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] In recent years a newer and much more accurate wide-band sensor, though more expensive, has become available.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Most stand-alone narrow-band meters have 10 LEDs and some have more.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Also common, narrow band meters in round housings with the standard mounting 52 and 67 mm (2+1⁄16 and 2+5⁄8 in) diameters, as other types of car 'gauges'.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Analogue 'needle' style gauges are also available.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] In theory, a stoichiometric mixture has just enough air to completely burn the available fuel.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] In practice, this is never quite achieved, due primarily to the very short time available in an internal combustion engine for each combustion cycle.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Most of the combustion process is completed in approximately 2 milliseconds at an engine speed of 6,000 revolutions per minute (100 revolutions per second, or 10 milliseconds per revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] For a four-stroke engine this would mean 5 milliseconds for each piston stroke, and 20 milliseconds to complete one 720 degree Otto cycle).
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] This is the time that elapses from the spark plug firing until 90% of the fuel–air mix is combusted, typically some 80 degrees of crankshaft rotation later.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Catalytic converters are designed to work best when the exhaust gases passing through them are the result of nearly perfect combustion.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] A perfectly stoichiometric mixture burns very hot and can damage engine components if the engine is placed under high load at this fuel–air mixture.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Due to the high flame temperatures at this mixture, detonation is possible under high load.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] (Detonation is known as knocking or pinging).
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Such detonation can cause serious engine damage as the uncontrolled burning of the fuel-air mix can create very high pressures in the cylinder.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] As a consequence, stoichiometric mixtures are only used under light to low-moderate load conditions.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] For acceleration and high-load conditions, a richer mixture (lower air–fuel ratio) is used to produce cooler combustion products and so avoid overheating of the cylinder head, and thus prevent detonation.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] The stoichiometric mixture for a gasoline engine is the ideal ratio of air to fuel that burns all fuel with no excess air.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] For gasoline fuel, the stoichiometric air–fuel mixture is about 14.7:1 i.e. for every one gram of fuel, 14.7 grams of air are required.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Any mixture greater than 14.7:1 is considered a lean mixture; any less than 14.7:1 is a rich mixture – given perfect (ideal) "test" fuel (gasoline consisting of solely *n*-heptane and iso-octane).
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] In reality, most fuels consist of a combination of heptane, octane, a handful of other alkanes, plus additives including detergents, and possibly oxygenators such as MTBE (methyl *tert*-butyl ether) or ethanol/methanol.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] These compounds all alter the stoichiometric ratio, with most of the additives pushing the ratio downward (oxygenators bring extra oxygen to the combustion event in liquid form that is released at the time of combustions; for MTBE-laden fuel, a stoichiometric ratio can be as low as 14.1:1).
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use an oxygen sensor or other feedback loops to control fuel to air ratio (lambda control), compensate automatically for this change in the fuel's stoichiometric rate by measuring the exhaust gas composition and controlling fuel volume.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use oxygen sensors can monitor the air–fuel ratio with an air–fuel ratio meter.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] In the typical air to natural gas combustion burner, a double-cross limit strategy is employed to ensure ratio control.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] The strategy involves adding the opposite flow feedback into the limiting control of the respective gas (air or fuel).
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] This assures ratio control within an acceptable margin.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] There are other terms commonly used when discussing the mixture of air and fuel in internal combustion engines.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Air-fuel ratio is the ratio between the *mass* of air and the mass of fuel in the air-fuel mix at any given moment.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] The mass is the mass of all constituents that compose the air or fuel, whether they take part in the combustion or not.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] For pure octane the stoichiometric mixture is approximately 15.1:1, or *λ* of 1.00 exactly.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] In naturally aspirated engines powered by octane, maximum power is frequently reached at AFRs ranging from 12.5 to 13.3:1 or *λ* of 0.850 to 0.901.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] The air-fuel ratio of 12:1 is considered as the maximum output ratio, whereas the air-fuel ratio of 16:1 is considered as the maximum fuel economy ratio.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Air–fuel equivalence ratio, *λ* (lambda), is the ratio of actual AFR to stoichiometry for a given mixture.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] *λ* = 1.0 is at stoichiometry, rich mixtures *λ* < 1.0, and lean mixtures *λ* > 1.0.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] There is a direct relationship between *λ* and AFR.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] To calculate AFR from a given *λ*, multiply the measured *λ* by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Alternatively, to recover *λ* from an AFR, divide AFR by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Because the composition of common fuels varies seasonally, and because many modern vehicles can handle different fuels when tuning, it makes more sense to talk about *λ* values rather than AFR.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Most practical AFR devices actually measure the amount of residual oxygen (for lean mixes) or unburnt hydrocarbons (for rich mixtures) in the exhaust gas.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] The **fuel–air equivalence ratio**, *Φ* (phi), of a system is defined as the ratio of the fuel-to-oxidizer ratio to the stoichiometric fuel-to-oxidizer ratio.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] where *m* represents the mass, *n* represents a number of moles, subscript st stands for stoichiometric conditions.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] The advantage of using equivalence ratio over fuel–oxidizer ratio is that it takes into account (and is therefore independent of) both mass and molar values for the fuel and the oxidizer.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] Consider, for example, a mixture of one mole of ethane (C 2H 6) and one mole of oxygen (O 2).
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] To compare it with the equivalence ratio, we need to determine the fuel–oxidizer ratio of ethane and oxygen mixture.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] This is not the case if one uses fuel–oxidizer ratio, which takes different values for different mixtures.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] In industrial fired heaters, power plant steam generators, and large gas-fired turbines, the more common terms are percent excess combustion air and percent stoichiometric air.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] For example, excess combustion air of 15 percent means that 15 percent more than the required stoichiometric air (or 115 percent of stoichiometric air) is being used.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] A combustion control point can be defined by specifying the percent excess air (or oxygen) in the oxidant, or by specifying the percent oxygen in the combustion product.
[src:flameout/air-fuel-ratio] An air–fuel ratio meter may be used to measure the percent oxygen in the combustion gas, from which the percent excess oxygen can be calculated from stoichiometry and a mass balance for fuel combustion.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] An **air-start system** is a power source used to provide the initial rotation to start large diesel engines and gas turbines.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] Compared to a gasoline (petrol) engine, a diesel engine has a very high compression ratio, an essential design feature, as it is the heat of compression that ignites the fuel.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] An electric starter with sufficient power to turn a large diesel engine would itself be so large as to be impractical so there is a need for an alternative system.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] An air start system has three main components along with various safety components, namely the air start injector, the distributor and the air receivers.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] When the system is initiated, starting air from the receivers is distributed by the distributor unit to each respective air start valve according to the firing order of the engine’s cylinders.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] Safety components include flame traps, to prevent air line explosions, a turning gear interlock which ensures that air-start cannot be initiated when the turning gear is engaged, relief valves and isolation valves, as well as drain valves at certain points along the system.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] Control components include the control valves and remote air-start valves.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] A direct start system as used on a marine slow-speed diesel is required to have up to 12 starts on a non-reversing engine or 6 starts on a reversible, or geared, engine.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] When starting the engine, compressed air is admitted to whichever cylinder has a piston just over top dead center, forcing it downward.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] As the engine starts to turn, the air-start valve on the next cylinder in line opens to continue the rotation.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] After several rotations, fuel is injected into the cylinders, the engine starts running and the air is cut off.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] To further complicate matters, a large engine is usually "blown over" first with zero fuel settings and the indicator cocks open, to prove that the engine is clear of any water build up and that everything is free to turn.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] After a successful blow ahead and a blow astern, the indicator cocks are closed on all the cylinders, and then the engine can be started on fuel.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] Significant complexity is added to the engine by using an air-start system, as the cylinder head must have an extra valve in each cylinder to admit the air in for starting, plus the required control systems.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] This added complexity and cost limits the use of air-starters to very large and expensive reciprocating engines.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] Another method of air-starting an internal combustion engine is by using compressed air or gas to drive a fluid motor in place of an electric motor.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] They can be used to start engines from 5 to 320 liters in size and if more starting power is necessary two or more motors can be used.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] Starters of this type are used in place of electric motors because of their lighter weight and higher reliability.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] They can also outlast an electric starter by a factor of three and are easier to rebuild.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] Engines operating in underground mining activities tend to operate on this type of starter system to reduce the risk of an electrical system igniting flammable material.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] All vane type air starters should have a lubricator installed to insure long-life and maximum performance.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] Lubricators give the moving parts a needed friction barrier, reduce metal corrosion and keep vanes sealed properly against the cylinder walls.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] Even the so-called lube-free air starters require lubrication to prolong trouble free life.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] Two basic lubricator devices are typically employed.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] One is an in-line or reservoir type that typically stores up to 2 quarts of lubricant, and is installed along the air supply line.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] The second style of lubricator is a small one shot device that dispenses a measured amount of lubricant every time the starter is engaged.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] Installed directly onto the air inlet of the starter, the in-line lubricators are self priming pneumatic pumps that require a 1/4″ lubrication line piped from as far away as 4 feet.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] Air Starter lubricators perform best using misting type, non-detergent oils such as diesel fuel or Marvel Mystery oil.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] If emissions are a concern, there are environmentally friendly type lubricants available on the market.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] Not all air starters require lubrication.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] Turbine type air starters do not require air motor lubrication, although some turbine air starters do use an oil filled transmission that may require periodic inspections and maintenance.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] Compressed air has been used to start gas turbine engines using air impingement starting (in which air is directed at the engine turbine blades through nozzles in the turbine casing, used on US Navy General Electric J79 engines).
[src:flameout/air-start-system] It is much more efficient to use an air turbine starter (ATS) which is usually mounted on an accessory gearbox.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] An early axial compressor turbojet had an ATS located in the compressor nose cone (eg particular variants of the J79).
[src:flameout/air-start-system] Air impingement starting was not used for US military aircraft after the F-4B, A-5A and F-5 as the pneumatic energy requirement was several times greater than when using an air turbine starter.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] The gas turbine compressor required to start a J79 with impingement starting was sufficient to start two J79 engines simultaneously in a B-58 when using air turbine starters.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] An ATS has its own turbine and gears to change its low torque and high speed to low speed and high torque at the engine mounting pad.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] Further gears in the engine gearbox connect to the engine shaft (high pressure spool on multi-spool engines).
[src:flameout/air-start-system] Compared with electric starters, air-starters have a higher power-to-weight ratio so are used on large engines as an electric starter would be too big and, with its cables, too heavy and expensive.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] However, for smaller engines, which don't need as much starter power, an electric starter is more suitable.
[src:flameout/air-start-system] It has a dual function as a generator (is known as a starter/generator) at speeds above which the engine no longer requires starter assistance.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The **air turborocket** is a form of combined-cycle jet engine.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The basic layout includes a gas generator, which produces high pressure gas, that drives a turbine/compressor assembly which compresses atmospheric air into a combustion chamber.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] This mixture is then combusted before leaving the device through a nozzle and creating thrust.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] There are many different types of air turborockets.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The various types generally differ in how the gas generator section of the engine functions.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] Air turborockets are often referred to as **turboramjets**, **turboramjet rockets**, **turborocket expanders**, and many others.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] As there is no consensus on which names apply to which specific concepts, various sources may use the same name for two different concepts.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The benefit of this setup is increased specific impulse over that of a rocket.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] For the same carried mass of propellant as a rocket motor, the overall output of the air turborocket is much higher.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] In addition, it provides thrust throughout a much wider speed range than a ramjet, yet is much cheaper and easier to control than a gas turbine engine.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The air turborocket fills a niche (in terms of cost, reliability, ruggedness, and duration of thrust) between the solid-fuel rocket motor and gas turbine engine for missile applications.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] A **turborocket** is a type of aircraft engine combining elements of a jet engine and a rocket.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] It typically comprises a multi-stage fan driven by a turbine, which is driven by the hot gases exhausting from a series of small rocket-like motors mounted around the turbine inlet.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust gases mix with the fan discharge air, and combust with the air from the compressor before exhausting through a convergent-divergent propelling nozzle.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] Once a jet engine goes high enough in an atmosphere, there is insufficient oxygen to burn the jet fuel.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The idea behind a turborocket is to supplement the atmospheric oxygen with an onboard supply.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] This allows operation at a much higher altitude than a normal engine would allow.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The turborocket design offers a mixture of benefits with drawbacks.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] It is not a true rocket, so it cannot operate in space.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] Cooling the engine is not a problem because the burner and its hot exhaust gases are located behind the turbine blades.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The air turboramjet engine is a combined cycle engine that merges aspects of turbojet and ramjet engines.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The turboramjet is a hybrid engine that essentially consists of a turbojet mounted inside a ramjet.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The turbojet core is mounted inside a duct that contains a combustion chamber downstream of the turbojet nozzle.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The turboramjet can be run in turbojet mode at takeoff and during low-speed flight but then switch to ramjet mode to accelerate to high Mach numbers.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The operation of the engine is controlled using bypass flaps located just downstream of the diffuser.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] During low-speed flight, controllable flaps close the bypass duct and force air directly into the compressor section of the turbojet.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] During high-speed flight, the flaps block the flow into the turbojet, and the engine operates like a ramjet using the *aft* combustion chamber to produce thrust.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The engine would start out operating as a turbojet during takeoff and while climbing to altitude.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] Upon reaching high subsonic speed, the portion of the engine downstream of the turbojet would be used as an afterburner to accelerate the plane above the speed of sound.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] At lower speeds, air passes through an inlet and is then compressed by an axial compressor.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] That compressor is driven by a turbine, which is powered by hot, high-pressure gas from a combustion chamber.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] These initial aspects are very similar to how a turbojet operates, however, there are several differences.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The first is that the combustor in the turboramjet is often separate from the main airflow.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] Instead of combining air from the compressor with fuel to combust, the turboramjet combustor may use hydrogen and oxygen, carried on the aircraft, as its fuel for the combustor.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The air compressed by the compressor bypasses the combustor and turbine section of the engine, where it is mixed with the turbine exhaust.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust can be designed to be fuel-rich (i.e., the combustor does not burn all the fuel) which, when mixed with the compressed air, creates a hot fuel-air mixture which is ready to burn again.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] More fuel is injected into this air where it is again combusted.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The exhaust is ejected through a propelling nozzle, generating thrust.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] Picture shown lacks required bypass ducting around the compressor for ramjet operation.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] Shown is a low bypass turbojet with re-heat.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] The turboramjet engine is used when space is constrained, as it takes up less space than separate ramjet and turbojet engines.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] Since a ramjet must already be traveling at high speeds before it will start working, a ramjet-powered aircraft is incapable of taking off from a runway under its own power; that is the advantage of the turbojet, which is a member of the gas turbine family of engines.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] A turbojet does not rely purely on the motion of the engine to compress the incoming air flow; instead, the turbojet contains some additional rotating machinery that compresses incoming air and allows the engine to function during takeoff and at slow speeds.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] In applications which stay relatively in the atmosphere and require longer durations of lower thrust over a specific speed range the air turborocket can have a weight advantage over the standard solid fuel rocket motor.
[src:flameout/air-turborocket] In terms of volumetric requirements, the rocket motor has the advantage due to the lack of inlet ducts and other air management devices.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The **Airbus A320 family** is a series of narrow-body airliners developed and produced by Airbus, and is the best-selling airliner ever built.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A320 aircraft programme was launched in March 1984, first flew on 22 February 1987, and was introduced in April 1988 by Air France.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The first member of the family was followed by the stretched A321 (first delivered in January 1994), the shorter A319 (April 1996), and the shortest variant, the A318 (July 2003).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Final assembly takes place in Toulouse in France; Hamburg in Germany; Tianjin in China since 2009; and Mobile, Alabama, in the United States since April 2016.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The twinjet has a six-abreast economy cross-section and came with either CFM56-5A or -5B, or IAE V2500 turbofan engines, except the A318.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A318 has either two CFM56-5B engines or a pair of PW6000 engines in place of the IAE V2500.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The family pioneered the use of digital fly-by-wire and side-stick flight controls in airliners.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The 31.4 m (103 ft) long A318 typically accommodates 107 to 132 passengers.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A320 is 37.6 m (123 ft) long and can accommodate 150 to 186 passengers.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The Airbus Corporate Jets are modified business jet versions of the standard commercial variants.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In December 2010, Airbus announced the re-engined A320neo (*new engine option*), which entered service with Lufthansa in January 2016.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] With more efficient turbofans and improvements including "sharklet" winglets, it offers up to 15% better fuel economy.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The previous A320 generation was renamed **A320ceo** (*current engine option*).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] American Airlines is the largest A320 family operator with 489 aircraft in its fleet, while IndiGo is the largest customer with 930 aircraft on order as of May 2026.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] A total of 20,169 A320 family aircraft have been ordered of which 12,670 units have been delivered and 11,374 units are in service with more than 375 operators .
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] It overtook the Boeing 737 family in terms of total fleet size in 2017, in terms of total orders in October 2019 and in terms of total deliveries in September 2025.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The global A320 fleet had completed more than 176 million flights over 328 million block hours since its entry into service.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A320ceo initially competed with the 737 Classic and the MD-80, then their successors, the 737 Next Generation (737NG) and the MD-90 respectively, while the 737 MAX is Boeing's response to the A320neo.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] When Airbus designed the A300 during the late 1960s and early 1970s, it envisaged a broad family of airliners with which to compete against Boeing and McDonnell Douglas, two established US aerospace manufacturers.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] From the moment of formation, Airbus had begun studies into derivatives of the Airbus A300B in support of this long-term goal.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Prior to the service introduction of the first Airbus airliners, engineers within Airbus had identified nine possible variations of the A300 known as A300B1 to B9.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] A 10th variation, conceived in 1973, later the first to be constructed, was designated the A300B10.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] It was a smaller aircraft which would be developed into the long-range Airbus A310.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Airbus then focused its efforts on the single-aisle market, which was dominated by the 737 and McDonnell Douglas DC-9.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Plans from a number of European aircraft manufacturers called for a successor to the relatively successful BAC One-Eleven, and to replace the 737-200 and DC-9.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Germany's MBB (*Messerschmitt-Bölkow-Blohm*), British Aircraft Corporation, Sweden's Saab and Spain's CASA worked on the *EUROPLANE*, a 180- to 200-seat aircraft.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] It was abandoned after intruding on A310 specifications.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] VFW-Fokker, Dornier and Hawker Siddeley worked on a number of 150-seat designs.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The design within the JET study that was carried forward was the JET2 (163 passengers), which then became the Airbus S.A1/2/3 series (Single Aisle), before settling on the A320 name for its launch in 1984.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Previously, Hawker Siddeley had produced a design called the HS.134 "Airbus" in 1965, an evolution of the HS.121 (formerly DH.121) *Trident*, which shared much of the general arrangement of the later JET3 study design.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The name "Airbus" at the time referred to a BEA requirement, rather than to the later international programme.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In June 1977 a new *Joint European Transport* (JET) programme was set up, established by British Aerospace (BAe), Aerospatiale, Dornier and Fokker.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] It was based at the then BAe (formerly Vickers) site in Weybridge, Surrey, UK.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Although the members were all Airbus' partners, they regarded the project as a separate collaboration from Airbus.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] This project was considered the forerunner of Airbus A320, encompassing the 130- to 188-seat market, powered by two CFM56s.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] It would have a cruise speed of Mach 0.84 (faster than the Boeing 737).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The programme was later transferred to Airbus, leading up to the creation of the *Single-Aisle* (SA) studies in 1980, led by former leader of the JET programme, Derek Brown.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The group looked at three different variants, covering the 125- to 180-seat market, called *SA1*, *SA2* and *SA3*.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Although unaware at the time, the consortium was producing the blueprints for the A319, A320 and A321, respectively.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The single-aisle programme created divisions within Airbus about whether to design a shorter-range twinjet rather than a longer-range quadjet wanted by the West Germans, particularly Lufthansa.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] However, works proceeded, and the German carrier would eventually order the twinjet.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In February 1981 the project was re-designated A320, with efforts focused on the blueprint formerly designated SA2.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] During the year, Airbus worked with Delta Air Lines on a 150-seat aircraft envisioned and required by the airline.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] They would measure 36.04 and 39.24 m (118 ft 3 in and 128 ft 9 in) respectively.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Airbus considered a fuselage diameter of "the Boeing 707 and 727, or do something better" and settled on a wider cross-section with a 3.7 m (12 ft 2 in) internal width, compared to Boeing's 3.45 m (11 ft 4 in).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Although heavier, this allowed the A320 to compete more effectively with the 737.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A320 wing went through several design stages, eventually measuring 33.91 m (111 ft 3 in).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The UK, France and West Germany wanted responsibility over final assembly and its associated work, known as "work-share arguments".
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The Germans requested an increased work-share of 40%, while the British wanted the major responsibilities to be swapped around to give partners production and research and development experience.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In the end, British work-share was increased from that of the two previous Airbuses.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] France was willing to commit to launch aid, or subsidies, while the Germans were more cautious.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The UK government was unwilling to provide funding for the tooling, requested by BAe and estimated at £250 million; it was postponed for three years.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] On 1 March 1984, the British government and BAe agreed that £50 million would be paid, whether the A320 flew or not, while the rest would be paid as a levy on each aircraft sold.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In 1984, the program cost was then estimated at £2 billion ($2.8 billion) by Flight International, equivalent to £7 billion today.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The programme was launched on 2 March 1984.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Air France was its first customer to sign a "letter of intent" for 25 A320s and options for 25 more at the 1981 Paris Air Show.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In October 1983, British Caledonian placed seven firm orders, bringing total orders to more than 80.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Cyprus Airways became the first customer to place an order for V2500-powered A320s in November 1984, followed by Pan Am with 16 firm orders and 34 options in January 1985, and then Inex Adria.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] One of the most significant orders occurred when Northwest Airlines placed an order for 100 A320s in October 1986, powered by CFM56 engines, later confirmed at the 1990 Farnborough Airshow.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] During A320 development, Airbus considered propfan technology, which was backed by Lufthansa.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] At the time unproven, the technology essentially consisted of a fan placed outside the engine nacelle, offering turbofan speeds and turboprop economics; ultimately, Airbus stuck with turbofans.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Power on the A320 was to be supplied by two CFM56-5-A1s rated at 111 kN (25,000 pounds-force).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] It was the only engine available until the arrival of the IAE V2500, offered by International Aero Engines, a group composed of Rolls-Royce plc, Pratt & Whitney, Japanese Aero Engine Corporation, Fiat and MTU.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The first V2500 variant, the V2500-A1, has a thrust output of 110 kN (25,000 pounds-force), hence the name.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] It is 4% more efficient than the CFM56, with cruise thrust-specific fuel consumption for the -A5 at 16.3 and 16.9 g/kN/s (0.58 and 0.60 lb/lbf/h) for the CFM56-5A1.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In the presence of then-French Prime Minister Jacques Chirac and the Prince and Princess of Wales, the first A320 was rolled out of final assembly line at Toulouse on 14 February 1987 and made its maiden flight on 22 February in 3 hours and 23 minutes.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The flight test programme took 1,200 hours over 530 flights.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] European Joint Aviation Authorities (JAA) certification was awarded on 26 February 1988.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The first A320 was delivered to Air France on 28 March, and began commercial service on 8 April with a flight between Paris and Berlin via Düsseldorf.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In 1988, the clean-sheet aircraft program cost was 5.486 billion French francs.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The first variation of the baseline A320 was the Airbus A321, also known as the *Stretched A320*, *A320-500* and *A325*.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Launched on 24 November 1988 after commitments for 183 aircraft from 10 customers were secured.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The aircraft was to be a minimally changed derivative, apart from minor wing modifications and a fuselage stretch.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The wing would incorporate double-slotted flaps and minor trailing edge modifications, increasing wing area from 124 m2 (1,330 sq ft) to 128 m2 (1,380 sq ft).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The fuselage was lengthened by four plugs (two ahead and two behind the wings), making the A321 6.94 metres (22 ft 9 in) longer than the A320 overall.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The length increase required enlarged overwing exits, which were repositioned in front of and behind the wings.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The centre fuselage and undercarriage were reinforced to accommodate an increase in maximum takeoff weight of 9,600 kg (21,200 lb), for a total of 83,000 kg (183,000 lb).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Final assembly for the A321 would be carried out in Germany (then West Germany), a first for any Airbus.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] This came after a dispute between the French, who claimed the move would incur $150 million (€135 million) in unnecessary expenditures associated with the new plant, and the Germans, who argued that it would be more productive for Airbus in the long run.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The second production line was located at Hamburg, which would also subsequently produce the smaller Airbus A319 and A318.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] For the first time, Airbus entered the bond market, through which it raised $480 million (€475 million) to finance development costs.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] An additional $180 million (€175 million) was borrowed from the European Investment Bank and private investors.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The maiden flight of the Airbus A321 came on 11 March 1993, when the prototype, registration F-WWIA, flew with IAE V2500 engines; the second prototype, equipped with CFM56-5B turbofans, flew in May.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Lufthansa and Alitalia were the first to order the stretched Airbuses, with 20 and 40 aircraft, respectively.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The first of Lufthansa's V2500-A5-powered A321s arrived on 27 January 1994, while Alitalia received its first CFM56-5B-powered aircraft on 22 March.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A319 was the second variation of the baseline A320.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The design was a "shrink", with origins in the 130- to 140-seat SA1, part of the Single-Aisle studies, which had been shelved as the consortium focused on its bigger siblings.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] After healthy sales of the A320/A321, Airbus focused once more on what was then known as the *A320M-7*, meaning A320 *minus seven fuselage frames*.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] It would provide direct competition for the 737-300/-700.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The shrink was achieved through the removal of four fuselage frames fore and three aft of the wing, cutting the overall length by 3.73 metres (12 ft 3 in).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Consequently, the number of overwing exits was reduced from four to two.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The bulk-cargo door was replaced by an aft container door, which can take in reduced height LD3-45 containers.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Minor software changes were made to accommodate the different handling characteristics; otherwise the aircraft was largely unchanged.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Airbus began offering the new model from 22 May 1992, with the actual launch of the $275 million (€250 million) programme occurring on 10 June 1993; the A319's first customer was ILFC, which signed for six aircraft.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] On 23 March 1995, the first A319 underwent final assembly at Airbus' German plant in Hamburg, where A321s were also assembled.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] It was rolled out on 24 August 1995, with the maiden flight taking place the following day.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The certification programme took 350 airborne hours involving two aircraft.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Certification for the CFM56-5B6/2-equipped variant was granted in April 1996, and qualification for the V2524-A5 started the following month.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Delivery of the first A319, to Swissair, occurred on 25 April 1996; it entered service by month's end.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In January 1997, an A319 broke a record during a delivery flight by flying the 6,645-kilometre (4,129 mi; 3,588 nmi) great circle route to Winnipeg, Manitoba from Hamburg in 9 hours and 5 minutes.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A319 has proven popular with low-cost airlines such as EasyJet, which purchased 172 of them.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A318, the fourth variant, was born out of mid-1990 studies between Aviation Industry Corporation of China (AVIC), Singapore Technologies Aerospace, Alenia and Airbus on a 95- to 125-seat aircraft project.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The programme was called the *AE31X*, and covered the 95-seat AE316 and 115- to 125-seat AE317.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The former would have had an overall length of 31.3 m (102 ft 8 in), while the AE317 was longer by 3.2 m (10 ft 6 in), at 34.5 m (113 ft 2 in).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Both share a wingspan of 31.0 m (101 ft 8 in) and a flight deck similar to that of the A320 family.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Costing $2 billion (€1.85 billion) to develop, aircraft production was to take place in China.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Simultaneously, Airbus was developing the Airbus A318.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In early 1998, Airbus revealed that it was designing a 100-seat aircraft based on the A320.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The AE31X project was terminated by September 1998, and Airbus officially announced the A318 at that year's Farnborough Airshow.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The aircraft was the smallest in Airbus's product range, and was developed coincidentally at the same time as the largest commercial aircraft in history, the Airbus A380.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] First called *A319M5* in as early as March 1995, it was shorter by 0.79 metres (2 ft 7 in) ahead of the wing and 1.6 metres (5 ft 3 in) behind.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] These cuts reduced passenger capacity from 124 on the A319 to 107 in a two-class layout.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The 107-seater was launched on 26 April 1999 with the options and orders count at 109 aircraft.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] After three years of design, the maiden flight took place at Hamburg on 15 January 2002.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Tests on the lead engine, the PW6000, revealed worse-than-expected fuel consumption.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Consequently, Pratt & Whitney abandoned the five-stage high-pressure compressor (HPC) for the MTU-designed six-stage HPC.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The 129 order book for the A318 shrank to 80, largely because of switches to other A320 family members.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] After 17 months of flight certification, during which 850 hours and 350 flights were accumulated, JAA certification was obtained for the CFM56-powered variant on 23 May 2003.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] On 22 July 2003, first delivery for launch customer Frontier Airlines occurred, entering service before the end of the month.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The Toulouse Blagnac final assembly line builds A320s, whereas the Hamburg Finkenwerder final assembly line builds A318s, A319s, and A321s.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The Airbus factory in Tianjin, China, assembles A319s, A320s, and A321s; A320s and A321s are also assembled at the Airbus Americas factory in Mobile, Alabama.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Airbus produced a total of 42 A320s per month in 2015, and expected to increase to 50 per month in 2017.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Production of parts takes place in a large number of countries around the world.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] For example, the centre fuselage is made in Hamburg, Germany; the horizontal stabiliser is produced in Getafe, Spain; and the rudder is produced in Harbin, China.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In June 2018, along a larger and modernised delivery centre, Airbus inaugurated its fourth Hamburg production line, with two seven-axis robots to drill 80% of fuselage upper side holes and autonomous mobile tooling platforms, following Design Thinking principles.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] By January 2019, Mobile was outputting 4.5 A320s per month, raising to 5 by the end of the year.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In September 2019, Airbus reached a milestone with the delivery of the 9000th A320-family aircraft, to Easyjet.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In October 2019, Airbus inaugurated a highly automated fuselage structure assembly line for A320 Family aircraft in Hamburg, showcasing an evolution in Airbus' industrial production system.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Production rates continue to rise, and Airbus aims to reach a production rate of 63 aircraft per month by 2021, which would result in the 10,000th delivery occurring early that year.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Due to the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on aviation, demand for new jets was reduced in 2020 and Airbus cut its monthly production from 60 to 40 A320s.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In October 2020, the 500th A320 built in Tianjin, an A320neo, was delivered to China Southern, twelve years after the final assembly line start in 2008.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In 2006, Airbus started the A320 Enhanced (A320E) programme as a series of improvements targeting a 4–5% efficiency gain, with large winglets (2%), aerodynamic refinements (1%), weight savings and a new aircraft cabin.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Engine improvements that reduced fuel consumption by 1% were made to the A320 in 2007 with the CFM56 Tech Insertion and in 2008 with the V2500Select (One).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In 2006, Airbus tested three styles of winglets intended to counteract the wing's lift-induced drag and wingtip vortices more effectively than the previous wingtip fence.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The first design type to be tested was developed by Airbus and based on work done by the AWIATOR programme.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The second type of winglet incorporated a more blended design and was designed by Winglet Technology, a company based in Wichita, Kansas, US.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Two aircraft were used in the flight test evaluation campaign – the prototype A320, which had been retained by Airbus for testing, and a new build aircraft which was fitted with both types of winglets before it was delivered to JetBlue.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Despite the anticipated efficiency gains and development work, Airbus announced that those winglets would not be offered to customers, claiming that the weight of the modifications required negated any aerodynamic benefits.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] On 17 December 2008, Airbus announced it was to begin flight testing an existing blended winglet design developed by Aviation Partners Inc. as part of an A320 modernisation programme using the A320 prototype.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Airbus launched the *sharklet* blended winglets during the November 2009 Dubai Airshow.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Installation adds 200 kg (440 lb) but offers a 3.5% fuel burn reduction on flights over 2,800 km (1,500 nmi; 1,700 mi), saving approximately US$220,000 and 700 t of CO2 per aircraft per year.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The 2.5-metre-tall (8 ft 2 in) wingtip devices are manufactured by Korean Air Aerospace Division.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In December 2011, Airbus filed suit in the western district of Texas over Aviation Partners' claims of infringement of its patents on winglet design and construction which were granted in 1993.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Airbus' lawsuit sought to reject responsibility to pay royalties to Aviation Partners for using its designs, despite work performed together with both parties to develop advanced winglets for the Airbus A320neo.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The lawsuit was confidentially settled in 2018, with the result that Airbus paid a large but undisclosed settlement.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The first sharklet-equipped Airbus A320 was delivered to Indonesia AirAsia on 21 December 2012, offering a 450 kg (990 lb) payload and 190 km (100 nmi; 120 mi) range increases over the original aircraft specifications.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In 2007, Airbus introduced a new enhanced, quieter cabin with better luggage storage and a more modern look and feel, and a new galley that reduced weight, increased revenue space and improved ergonomics and design for food hygiene and recycling.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] It offered a new air purifier with filters and a catalytic converter, removing unpleasant smells from the air before it is pumped into the cabin, as well as LEDs for mood lighting and a new passenger service unit (PSU).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Offering 10% more overhead bin volume, more shoulder room, a weight reduction, a new intercom and in-flight entertainment system, noise reduction and slimmer PSU, the enhanced cabin can be retrofitted.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The flight crew controls the cabin through touchscreen displays.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A320neo (*neo* for *new engine option*) is an incremental development launched on 1 December 2010, making its first flight on 25 September 2014 and introduced by Lufthansa on 25 January 2016.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Re-engined with CFM International LEAP-1A or Pratt & Whitney PW1000G engines and with large sharklets, it was designed to be 15% more fuel efficient.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Its three variants are based on the previous A319, A320 and A321.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Airbus received 6,031 orders by March 2018 and delivered 318 by May 2018.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The original family was renamed A320ceo, for *current engine option*.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] As of July 2024, IndiGo has 173 Airbus A320neos in service, making it the largest operator of this type of aircraft.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In 2006, Airbus was studying a future replacement for the A320 series, tentatively dubbed as *NSR* or "New Short-Range aircraft".
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The follow-on aircraft to replace the A320 was to be named *A30X*.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In 2007, Airbus North America President Barry Eccleston stated that the earliest the aircraft could have been available was 2017.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In January 2010, John Leahy, Airbus's chief operating officer-customers, stated that an all-new single-aisle aircraft was unlikely to be constructed before 2024 or 2025.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The Airbus A320 family are narrow-body aircraft with a retractable tricycle landing gear and powered by two wing pylon-mounted turbofan engines.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] After the oil price rises of the 1970s, Airbus needed to minimise the trip fuel costs of the A320.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] To that end, it adopted composite primary structures for the empennage with a conventional tail configuration, centre-of-gravity control using fuel, a glass cockpit with side-stick controllers and a two-crew flight deck.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Airbus claimed the 737-300 burns 35% more fuel and has a 16% higher operating cost per seat than the V2500-powered A320.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Its wing is long and thin, offering better aerodynamic efficiency because of the higher aspect ratio than the competing 737 and MD-80.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The Airbus A320 family are low-wing cantilever monoplanes with a conventional empennage with a single vertical stabiliser and rudder.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Compared to other airliners of the same class, the A320 features a wider single-aisle cabin of 3.95 metres (156 in) outside diameter, compared to the 3.8 m (148 in) of the Boeing 737 or 757, and larger overhead bins.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Its cargo hold can accommodate unit load device containers.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A320 airframe includes composite materials and aluminium alloys to save weight and reduce the total number of parts to decrease the maintenance costs.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Its tail assembly is made almost entirely of such composites by CASA, which also builds the elevators, main landing gear doors, and rear fuselage parts.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A320 flight deck features a full glass cockpit, rather than the hybrid versions found in previous airliners.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] It is also equipped with an Electronic Flight Instrument System (EFIS) with side-stick controllers.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A320 has an Electronic Centralised Aircraft Monitor (ECAM) to give the flight crew information about all of the systems on the aircraft.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The only analogue instruments were the radio-magnetic indicator and brake pressure indicator.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Since 2003, the A320 has featured liquid crystal display (LCD) units on the flight deck instead of the original cathode-ray tube (CRT) displays.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] These include both main displays and the backup artificial horizon, which also previously had an analogue display.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Airbus offers an avionics upgrade for older A320 aircraft, the In-Service Enhancement Package, to keep them updated.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Digital head-up displays are also available.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] At its introduction, fly-by-wire and flight envelope protection was a new experience for many pilots.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] All following Airbuses have similar human/machine interface and systems control philosophy to facilitate cross-type qualification with minimal training.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Early A320s used the Intel 80186 and Motorola 68010.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In 1988, the flight management computer contained six Intel 80286 CPUs, running in three logical pairs, with 2.5 megabytes of memory.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The Joint Aviation Authorities (JAA) issued the type certificate for the A320 on 26 February 1988.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] As of March 2024, the global A320 fleet had 99.7 per cent operational reliability in the last 12 months and completed more than 176 million flights over 328 million block hours since its entry into service.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] After an incident where JetBlue Flight 1230 experienced a rapid descent when solar radiation inadvertently corrupted flight data on 30 October 2025, Airbus and EASA issued a mandatory safety notice at the end of November for over 6,000 aircraft, over half of the family's fleet.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Most only required a patch reverting the flight control software for the aircraft's elevators that could be completed in three hours, while about 900 with older software needed a replacement of onboard hardware.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The impact on airline operations was relatively minor; although there were some delays, most airlines were able to complete the change within three days.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Avianca notably suffered bigger impacts as it had upgraded 92% of its aircraft to the software version that it had to roll back from, resulting in the airline closing ticket sales until 8 December.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The update has been cited as a contributing factor to the major 2025 IndiGo disruption.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A320 family was developed to compete with the Boeing 737 Classics (−300/-400/-500) and the McDonnell Douglas MD-80/90 series, and has since faced challenges from the Boeing 737 Next Generation (−600/-700/-800/-900) and the 717 during its two decades in service.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] As of 2010, the A320 family also faced competition from Embraer's E-195 (to the A318) and the CSeries being developed by Bombardier (later Airbus A220) to the A318/A319.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Airbus has delivered 8,605 A320 family aircraft since their certification/first delivery in early 1988, with another 6,056 on firm order (as of 31 December 2018).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In comparison, Boeing has shipped 10,444 737-series aircraft since late 1967, including 8,918 since March 1988, and has a further 4,763 on firm order (as of 31 December 2018).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] By September 2018, there were 7,251 A320ceo family aircraft in service versus 6,757 737NGs, while Airbus expected to deliver 3,174 A320neos compared with 2,999 Boeing 737 MAX through 2022.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Airbus sold the A320 well to low-cost startups and offering a choice of engines could make them more attractive to airlines and lessors than the single-sourced 737, but CFM engines are extremely reliable.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The six-month head start of the A320neo allowed Airbus to rack up 1,000 orders before Boeing announced the MAX.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A321 has outsold the 737-900 three to one, as the A321neo is again dominating the 737-9 MAX, to be joined by the 737-10 MAX.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] A Checks are every 750 flight hours and structural inspections are at 6 and 12-year intervals.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The baseline A320 has given rise to a family of aircraft which share a common design but with passenger capacity ranges from 100, on the A318, to 220, on the A321.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Because the four A320 variants share the same flight deck, all have the same pilot type rating.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Today all variants are available as corporate jets.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] An A319 variant known as A319LR was also developed.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Military versions like A319 MPA also exist.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] American Airlines is the largest airline operator of the A320 family of aircraft, with 392 aircraft in service as of 30 September 2017.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Technically, the name "A320" only refers to the original mid-sized aircraft, but it is often informally used to indicate any of the A318/A319/A320/A321 family.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] All variants have had 180-minute ETOPS (extended-range twin-engine operational performance standards) certification capacity since 2004 (EASA) and 2006 (FAA).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The Airbus A318 is the smallest member of the Airbus A320 family.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A318 carries up to 132 passengers and has a maximum range of 5,700 km (3,600 mi; 3,100 nmi).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The aircraft entered service in July 2003 with Frontier Airlines, and shares a common type rating with all other Airbus A320 family variants, allowing existing A320 family pilots to fly the aircraft without the need for further training.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] It is the largest commercial aircraft certified by the European Aviation Safety Agency for steep approach operations, allowing flights at airports such as London City Airport.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Relative to other Airbus A320 family variants, the A318 has sold in only small numbers with total orders for only 80 aircraft placed as of 31 October 2015.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Also known as the A320M-7, it is a shortened, minimum-change version of the A320 with four frames fore of the wing and three frames aft of the wing removed.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] With a similar fuel capacity as the A320-200 and fewer passengers, the range with 124 passengers in a two-class configuration extends to 6,650 km (3,590 nmi; 4,130 mi), or 6,850 km (3,700 nmi; 4,260 mi) with the "sharklets".
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Although identical to those of the A320, these engines are derated because of the A319's lower MTOW.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] When configured with a single overwing exit per side, seating capacity is limited to 145, while this is increased to 160 with two overwing exits.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A319 was developed at the request of ILFC.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A319's launch customer, in fact, was ILFC, which had placed an order for six A319s by 1993.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Anticipating further orders by Swissair and Alitalia, Airbus decided to launch the programme on 10 June 1993.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Final assembly of the first A319 began on 23 March 1995 and it was first introduced with Swissair in April 1996.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The direct Boeing competitor is the Boeing 737-700.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] A total of 1,460 of the A319ceo model have been delivered with 24 remaining on order as of 30 September 2017.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] A 1998 A319 was $35 million new; the value was halved by 2009, and reached scrap levels by 2019.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A319CJ (rebranded the ACJ319) is the corporate jet version of the A319.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] It incorporates removable extra fuel tanks (up to six additional centre tanks) which are installed in the cargo compartment, and an increased service ceiling of 12,500 m (41,000 ft).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Range with eight passengers' payload and auxiliary fuel tanks (ACTs) is up to 11,000 kilometres (6,900 mi).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Upon resale, the aircraft can be reconfigured as a standard A319 by removing its extra tanks and corporate cabin outfit, thus maximising its resale value.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] It was formerly also known as the ACJ, or Airbus Corporate Jet, while starting with 2014 it has the marketing designation *ACJ319*.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The aircraft seats up to 39 passengers, but may be outfitted by the customers into any configuration.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] GmbH & CO KG, MJET and Reliance Industries are among its users.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A319CJ competes with other ultralarge-cabin corporate jets such as the Boeing 737-700-based Boeing Business Jet (BBJ) and Embraer Lineage 1000, as well as with large-cabin and ultralong-range Gulfstream G650, Gulfstream G550 and Bombardier's Global 6000.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] It is powered by the same engine types as the A320.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A319CJ was used by the *Escadron de Transport, d'Entraînement et de Calibration* which is in charge of transportation for France's officials and also by the Flugbereitschaft of the German Air Force for transportation of Germany's officials.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] An ACJ serves as a presidential or official aircraft of Armenia, Azerbaijan, Brazil, Bulgaria, Czech Republic, Germany, Italy, Malaysia, Slovakia, Thailand, Turkey, Ukraine, and Venezuela.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] These aircraft, the first to be manufactured, were delivered to Air Inter – later acquired by Air France – and British Airways as a result of an order from British Caledonian made prior to its acquisition.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The primary differences from the -100 were the -200's wingtip fences and increased fuel capacity, providing increased range.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] A total of 4,512 of the A320ceo model have been delivered, with 220 remaining on order as of 30 September 2017.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The closest Boeing competitor is the 737-800.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In 1988, the value of a new A320 was $30 million, reaching $40 million by the end of the 1990s, a 30% increase lower than inflation; it dipped to $37 million after 2001, then peaked to $47 million in 2008, and stabilised at $40–42 million until the transition to the A320neo.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In 2018, its list price was US$101.0 million.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] As the A320 was beginning operations in 1988, the A321 was launched as its first derivative the same year.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A321 fuselage is stretched by 6.93 metres (22 ft 9 in), with a 4.27 m (14 ft 0 in) front plug immediately forward of wing and a 2.67 m (8 ft 9 in) rear plug.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] To maintain performance, double-slotted flaps were included, in addition to increasing the wing area by 4 m2 (43 sq ft), to 128 m2 (1,380 sq ft).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The maiden flight of the first of two prototypes came on 11 March 1993.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A321-100 entered service in January 1994 with Lufthansa.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] As the A321-100 range was less than the A320, development of the heavier and longer range A321-200 began in 1995.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The higher range was achieved through higher thrust engines (V2533-A5 or CFM56-5B3), minor structural strengthening, and an increase in fuel capacity with the installation of one or two optional 2,990 L (790 US gal; 660 imp gal) tanks in the rear underfloor hold.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Its fuel capacity was increased to 30,030 L (7,930 US gal; 6,610 imp gal) and its maximum takeoff weight to 93,000 kg (205,000 lb).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] It first flew in December 1996 and entered service with Monarch Airlines in April 1997.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] A total 1,784 units of the A321ceo model have been delivered, with seven remaining on order as of 30 September 2023.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] A programme to convert A320 and A321 aircraft into freighters was set up by Airbus Freighter Conversion GmbH.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Airframes were to be converted by Elbe Flugzeugwerke GmbH (EFW) in Dresden, Germany, and Zhukovsky, Russia.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Launch customer AerCap signed a firm contract on 16 July 2008 to convert 30 of its passenger A320/A321s into A320/A321P2F (passenger to freighter).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] However, on 3 June 2011, Airbus announced all partners would end the passenger-to-freighter programme, citing high demand on used airframes for passenger service.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Finally, on 17 June 2015 ST Aerospace signed agreements with Airbus and EFW for a collaboration to launch the A320/A321 passenger-to-freighter (P2F) conversion programme.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In August 2019, Qantas was announced as launch operator for the A321P2F converted freighter.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Titan Airways received its first of three A321P2F in January 2021.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The initial converted aircraft first flew on 22 January 2020, to be delivered to Vallair, and secured EASA supplementary type certificate in February.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] It was to replace older converted Boeing 757s with 14 main deck and 10 lower deck positions, carrying up to 27.9 t (62,000 lb) over 4,300 km (2,600 mi; 2,300 nmi).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] Airbus sees a market for 1,000 narrowbody conversions over the 2020-2040 period.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] On 27 October 2020, the first A321P2F was delivered to Qantas Airways, with windows and exit doors removed, and a large hydraulically actuated main cargo door installed.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] After EFW began the first A320 conversion in March 2021, the A320P2F made its maiden three-hour flight on 8 December from Singapore.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The aircraft was first delivered in 2006, and its first cargo operator was to be Nairobi-based Astral Aviation from the second quarter of 2022, leased from Middle Eastern lessor Vaayu Group.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A320P2F received its supplemental type certification at the end of March 2022.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] The A320P2F is suitable for express domestic as well as regional operations and can accommodate up to 27 tonnes (60,000 lb) over 3,500 kilometres (2,200 mi; 1,900 nmi), offering space for 14 large containers/pallets on the main deck and 10 LD3-type containers on the lower deck.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In late 2020, the Indian Defence Ministry greenlit the modification of six Air India A320s into Netra Mk2 airborne early warning and control aircraft for ₹105 billion (US$1.42 billion).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] They were to complement two Indian-built Netra and three Israeli-and-Russian-made Phalcons of the Indian Air Force.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In 2019, the DRDO's Centre for Airborne Systems (CABS) initiated a programme to fulfil an Indian Air Force requirement for signals intelligence gathering, communications jamming, electronic warfare and spoofing roles.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In 2023, at Aero India, DRDO showcased a 1:32 scale model of the SCA system, outlining its capabilities.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] DRDO plans to base the SCA system on a preowned Airbus A319 or Airbus A321.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p01] In February 2024, the Indian Defence Ministry's Defence Acquisition Council (DAC) granted Acceptance of Necessity (AoN) for the acquisition of three SCA systems initially at an estimated cost of ₹63 billion (US$717.14 million).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] As of March 2026, there are 11,508 A320 family aircraft in commercial service with over 375 operators.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] The five largest operators are American Airlines (489), China Eastern Airlines (391), IndiGo (367), easyJet (356) and China Southern Airlines (353).
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] In addition, 1,040 A320ceo family aircraft (41 A318s, 292 A319ceos, 619 A320ceos and 88 A321ceos) and 5 A320neo family aircraft (3 A320neos + 2 A321neos) were out of service through retirement or write-off.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] Air France, British Airways, and Frontier Airlines are the only operators to have operated all four variants of the A320ceo family.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] Middle East Airlines received two milestone aircraft.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] The first was an A320ceo with manufacturer serial number (MSN) 5,000 on 20 January 2012.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] Eight years later, on 9 October 2020, the airline received MSN 10,000, an A321neo, at the celebration of its 75th anniversary.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] In 2017, the A320 family became the most operated airliner family with a fleet of 6,965 aircraft, surpassing the Boeing 737 fleet of 6,864 aircraft.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] In December 2022, over 10,000 A320 family aircraft were operated by more than 330 airlines, completing more than 158 million flights, or 292 million hours in the air.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] The A320ceo family was the fastest-selling airliner from 2005 to 2007.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] Its successor, the A320neo family, improved on this with 1,420 orders and commitments in less than a year in 2011.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] In November 2013, the A320 family aircraft reached 10,000 orders.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] As of 2017, there were 6,965 A320 Family aircraft in service, more than the 6,864 Boeing 737s, making it the most-operated airliner ever.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] In October 2019, the A320 family became the highest-selling airliner family with 15,193 orders, surpassing the Boeing 737's total of 15,136.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] In August 2021, the A320 family passed the 10,000 delivery mark, 33 years after its introduction, versus 50 years for the Boeing 737, which passed the 10,000 delivery mark in March 2018.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] On 16 December 2021, the last member of the A320ceo family, an A321ceo (MSN 10315), was delivered from the Airbus Mobile assembly line in Alabama to Delta Air Lines, registered N129DN.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] In July 2022, total orders for the A320neo family reached 8,502, exceeding the total orders for the A320ceo family of 8,120.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] In June 2023, total orders for the A321neo reached 5,163, surpassing total orders for the A320ceo of 4,763, and making it the most-ordered variant of the A320 family.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] In July 2023, total orders for the A321neo reached 5,259, surpassing the record 5,205 orders for the Boeing 737-800, making it the most ordered variant of any airliner in history.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] In December 2023, the A320neo family became the first of airliner generations to reach a record order of 10,000 units and an order backlog of 7,000 units.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] In September 2025, the A320 family surpassed the Boeing 737 as the most-delivered jet aircraft and thus the best-selling airliner ever.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] In May 2026, the A320 family became the first airliner programme to reach 20,000 orders.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] As of May 2026, a total of 12,670 A320 family aircraft have been delivered, with 6 A320ceos (2 A319s and 4 A320s from two defunct airlines) remaining in the backlog.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] In the first five months of 2026, Airbus delivered 198 A320neo family aircraft, comprising 2 A319neo, 68 A320neos and 128 A321neos.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] The A320 family backlog remains over the 7,000 mark, of which A321s comprise 70%, and total orders have reached 20,169, while total orders for the competing Boeing 737 have increased slightly to 17,393 aircraft, of which 12,572 have been delivered.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] As of June 2024, across the entire A320 family, 180 major aviation accidents and incidents have occurred, including 38 hull loss accidents. resulting in a total of 1490 fatalities.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] The deadliest incident involving the A320 family was the bombing of Metrojet Flight 9268 on 31 October 2015, with 224 fatalities.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] The A320 family has experienced 50 incidents in which several flight displays were lost.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] As of 2015, the Airbus A320 family had experienced 0.12 fatal hull loss accidents for every million takeoffs and 0.26 total hull loss accidents for every million takeoffs.
[src:flameout/airbus-a320-p02] As of 2023, the Airbus A320 family had experienced 0.095 (0.08 for A320ceo and 0.11 for A320neo) fatal hull loss accidents for every million takeoffs and 0.14 (0.17 for A320ceo and 0.11 for A320neo) total hull loss accidents for every million takeoffs.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus originated from **Airbus Industrie GIE**, a consortium of European aerospace companies established in 1970 to produce a wide-body aircraft to compete with American-built airliners.
[src:flameout/airbus] In 2000, the consortium's parent firms—Aérospatiale-Matra of France, DASA of Germany, and CASA of Spain—merged to form the **European Aeronautic Defence and Space Company** (**EADS**), which later acquired full ownership of Airbus Industrie.
[src:flameout/airbus] Reflecting its multinational origins, the company operates offices and assembly plants in France, Germany, Spain, and the United Kingdom, along with more recent additions in Canada, Malaysia, the United States, Morocco, and India.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus's headquarters are legally registered in Leiden, Netherlands, while day-to-day management is conducted from the company's main office in Blagnac, France.
[src:flameout/airbus] The *SE* in its name denotes *Societas Europaea*, a public company under European Union corporate law.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus is led by CEO Guillaume Faury and is included in the EURO STOXX 50 stock market index.
[src:flameout/airbus] Since its inception in 2000, the company's shares have been listed on the Paris, Frankfurt, and four Spanish stock exchanges, including the Bolsa de Madrid.
[src:flameout/airbus] The company traces its origins to the formation of the *Airbus Industrie GIE*, a consortium of European aerospace companies established in 1970 to produce a wide-body aircraft to compete with American-built airliners.
[src:flameout/airbus] France's state-owned Aérospatiale owned 37.9% of Airbus Industrie, West Germany's Deutsche Airbus also owned 37.9%, British Aerospace held 20%, and Spain's largely state-owned CASA owned 4.2%.
[src:flameout/airbus] In 2000, the European Aeronautic Defence and Space Company (EADS) was established through the merger of Aérospatiale and Matra of France, DASA (the successor to Deutsche Airbus) of Germany, and CASA.
[src:flameout/airbus] EADS held 100% of *Eurocopter* *S.A.*, established in 1992 and later renamed Airbus Helicopters, along with 80% of Airbus Industrie GIE, which was quickly reorganised as *Airbus S.A.S.*, a simplified joint-stock company.
[src:flameout/airbus] In 2006, EADS acquired the remaining 20% of Airbus S.A.S. from BAE Systems (the successor of British Aerospace).
[src:flameout/airbus] EADS was renamed *Airbus Group N.V.* in 2014 and *Airbus Group S.E.* in 2015.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus S.A.S. and Airbus Group S.E. were merged in January 2017, and in April 2017 the combined entity adopted the name Airbus SE.
[src:flameout/airbus] Since then, Airbus SE has owned the commercial aircraft manufacturing operations while also serving as the parent company of the other two divisions, Airbus Defence and Space and Airbus Helicopters.
[src:flameout/airbus] The Airbus product line started with the A300 in 1972, the world's first wide-body, twinjet aircraft.
[src:flameout/airbus] Initial sales were slow, leading to calls to end the Airbus program.
[src:flameout/airbus] However, the aircraft would greatly benefit from the 1976 introduction of the ETOPS 90 rule, which allowed twinjet aircraft to operate up to 90 minutes—an increase from 60 minutes—away from the nearest airport.
[src:flameout/airbus] Under the new rule, the A300 was able to operate over the North Atlantic, the Bay of Bengal, and the Indian Ocean, making it a more efficient alternative to the trijets and four-engined aircraft offered by competitors, leading to renewed airline interest and a sharp increase in sales.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus then developed the A310 to meet demand for a shorter-body but longer-range version of the A300.
[src:flameout/airbus] The aircraft also introduced a glass cockpit, which eliminated the need for a flight engineer, and a redesigned rear fuselage that used space more efficiently, creating additional capacity.
[src:flameout/airbus] The A310 was manufactured from 1981 to 1998.
[src:flameout/airbus] These design changes were later incorporated into the A300, resulting in the A300-600.
[src:flameout/airbus] Building on its success with the A300, Airbus developed the narrow-body A320 aircraft that was launched in 1987, which became and remains a major commercial success.
[src:flameout/airbus] The A320 was the first commercial jet to use a digital fly-by-wire control system.
[src:flameout/airbus] All Airbus models developed since have adopted cockpit systems similar to the A320, making it easier for crews to transition between aircraft types.
[src:flameout/airbus] The success of the A320 led Airbus to introduce a lengthened version, the A321, in 1993, followed by the shorter A319 in 1995 and the even shorter A318 in 2002.
[src:flameout/airbus] In 2016, Airbus re-engineered the narrow-body family under a programme called the A320neo (*new engine option*).
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus also embarked on an effort to develop new wide-body aircraft derived from the cross-section of the A300, but with greater range and seating capacity and integrating technologies developed from the A320 programme.
[src:flameout/airbus] This effort led to the introduction of the four-engine A340 in 1991 and the twinjet A330 in 1992.
[src:flameout/airbus] At that time, Airbus wanted to offer a four-engined jet aircraft to allow for transpacific flights.
[src:flameout/airbus] However, during the aircraft's development, new ETOPS rules extended twinjet operations to 120 minutes in 1986 and 180 minutes in 1989.
[src:flameout/airbus] Although these changes hurt sales of the A340, they greatly benefited the A330.
[src:flameout/airbus] Production of the A340 ended in 2011, while the A330 was re-engineered as the A330neo (*new engine option*) in 2018.
[src:flameout/airbus] In 2005, Airbus introduced the world's largest passenger airliner: the A380 is a four-engine aircraft with two full-length passenger seating decks.
[src:flameout/airbus] Intended to challenge the dominance of the Boeing 747 in the long-haul market, the A380 was ultimately a money-losing venture for Airbus due to large development costs and limited sales arising from high operating costs, and production ended in December 2021.
[src:flameout/airbus] The A350, a wide-body, twinjet aircraft, was introduced in 2015.
[src:flameout/airbus] The A350 was the first Airbus aircraft that was largely produced from carbon-fiber-reinforced polymers.
[src:flameout/airbus] It is longer and wider than the fuselage used on the A300, A310, A330, and A340.
[src:flameout/airbus] A second narrow-body jet was added to the product list in 2018 when Airbus gained control of the Bombardier CSeries programme, and rebranded it as the A220.
[src:flameout/airbus] The jet offers five-abreast seating compared to the six-abreast seating on the A320.
[src:flameout/airbus] In December 2024, it was reported that the total aircraft delivery in the year for Airbus has reached 643 units, with 84 planes delivered in November 2024 alone.
[src:flameout/airbus] Subsequently, in January 2025, it was reported that Airbus had successfully delivered 766 aircraft to its customers out of 878 orders in the entire 2024, marking a 4% increase from the previous year.
[src:flameout/airbus] In October 2025, the A320 overtook the Boeing 737 as the most delivered airliner.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus Corporate Jets markets and modifies new aircraft for private and corporate customers.
[src:flameout/airbus] It has a model range that parallels the commercial aircraft offered by the company.
[src:flameout/airbus] Following the entry of the 737-based Boeing Business Jet, Airbus joined the business jet market with the A319 Corporate Jet in 1997.
[src:flameout/airbus] Although the term Airbus Corporate Jet was initially used only for the A319CJ, it is now often used for all models, including VIP widebodies.
[src:flameout/airbus] As of December 2008, 121 corporate and private jets are operating, and 164 aircraft have been ordered.
[src:flameout/airbus] The company also owns 10% of Dassault Aviation, which builds the Falcon family of smaller business jets.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus Defence and Space markets and either builds or modifies new aircraft for military use.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus became increasingly interested in developing and selling to the military aviation market in the late 1990s.
[src:flameout/airbus] It embarked on two main fields of development: aerial refuelling with the Airbus A310 MRTT (Multi-Role Tanker Transport) and later the Airbus A330 MRTT, and tactical airlift with the Airbus A400M Atlas.
[src:flameout/airbus] The company has also continued to market and assemble some military aircraft previously offered by the companies that formed Airbus, notably CASA.
[src:flameout/airbus] The A310 and A330-based MRTT aircraft are conversions of civilian airliners.
[src:flameout/airbus] The aircraft are called multi-role tanker transports because, in addition to their aerial refuelling capability, the aircraft can also be configured for troop transport, medevac, and cargo transportation.
[src:flameout/airbus] The A400M Atlas is a four-engine, turboprop-powered tactical transport aircraft.
[src:flameout/airbus] The A400M is sized between the American-made C-130 and the C-17 transports, and while it can carry heavier loads than the C-130, its turboprop engines allow it to retain the ability to use rough landing strips.
[src:flameout/airbus] The A400M was developed for European NATO members Belgium, France, Germany, Luxembourg, Spain, Turkey, and the UK, as an alternative to relying on foreign aircraft.
[src:flameout/airbus] During development, the A400M programme faced delays and cost overruns; with customer nations stepping in to offer additional subsidies.
[src:flameout/airbus] The first aircraft was delivered to the French Air Force in 2013, and by 2023, more than 100 aircraft had been built.
[src:flameout/airbus] The Defence and Space division also markets and assembles the EADS CASA C295, a smaller tactical transport aircraft, that was designed and initially manufactured by the Spanish aerospace company CASA.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus Helicopters builds and markets new rotorcraft for civilian and military use.
[src:flameout/airbus] The division was founded formed in 1992 as the Eurocopter Group, through the merger of the helicopter divisions of Aérospatiale and DASA (two of the founding companies of Airbus).
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus Helicopters is the foremost player in the turbine helicopter industry in terms of both revenue and deliveries.
[src:flameout/airbus] The division's civilian products include the single-engine H125 and H130, the light twin-engine H135 and H145, the medium twin-engine H155 and H160, the super medium twin-engine H175, and the heavy twin-engine H215 and H225.
[src:flameout/airbus] Military products include the Tiger attack helicopter, along with militarised versions of the H125, H135, H145, H160, H175, H215, and H225.
[src:flameout/airbus] The company owns 62.5% of NHIndustries joint venture, which builds the NH90 military utility helicopter.
[src:flameout/airbus] Commercial aircraft generated 74% of total revenue for the Airbus group in 2018 and 72% in 2023.
[src:flameout/airbus] This line of business was the first one in the world to begin field tests with TETRA Enhanced Data Service (TEDS).
[src:flameout/airbus] The Airbus Military division, which manufactured tanker, transport, and mission aircraft; Airbus Helicopters, the world's largest helicopter supplier; Astrium, provided systems for aerial, land, naval, and civilian security applications, including Ariane, Galileo, and Cassidian.
[src:flameout/airbus] Through Cassidian, EADS was a partner in the Eurofighter consortium as well as in the MBDA missile systems manufacturer.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus Helicopters, formerly known as Eurocopter, is a helicopter manufacturing and support company.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus has several final assembly lines for different models and markets.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus, however, has a number of other plants in different European locations, reflecting its foundation as a consortium.
[src:flameout/airbus] For aircraft assembled in Europe, aircraft parts often move between the different factories and the assembly lines via the use of the Beluga and BelugaXL, a fleet modified aircraft capable of carrying entire sections of fuselage.
[src:flameout/airbus] For aircraft assembled in China and the United States, the parts needed to build an aircraft meet in a single European location where they are loaded onto ships for the final journey to the assembly line.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus opened an assembly plant for the A320 family of aircraft in Tianjin, China in 2009.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus started constructing a $350 million component manufacturing plant in Harbin, China in July 2009.
[src:flameout/airbus] It was fully operational by early 2011, the 30,000 square metre plant manufactures composite parts and assembles composite work-packages for the A350 XWB, A320 families and future Airbus programmes.
[src:flameout/airbus] Harbin Aircraft Industry Group Corporation, Hafei Aviation Industry Company Ltd, AviChina Industry & Technology and other Chinese partners hold an 80% stake in the plant while Airbus controls the remaining 20%.
[src:flameout/airbus] In 2022, the Tianjin plant finished upgrading works to allow for production of A321.
[src:flameout/airbus] In 2023, the Tianjin final assembly plant started construction to be expanded with a second production line.
[src:flameout/airbus] North America plays a crucial role for Airbus, both in terms of aircraft sales and suppliers.
[src:flameout/airbus] Of the approximately 5,300 Airbus jetliners sold worldwide, 2,000 are ordered by North American customers.
[src:flameout/airbus] These orders span Airbus' entire product line, from the compact A318 to the massive A380, accommodating 107 to 565 passengers.
[src:flameout/airbus] Notably, US contractors contribute significantly, supporting around 120,000 jobs and generating an estimated $5.5 billion in business.
[src:flameout/airbus] For instance, one variant of the A380 boasts 51% American content in terms of work share value.
[src:flameout/airbus] Plans for a Mobile, Alabama aircraft assembly plant were unveiled by Airbus CEO Fabrice Brégier from the Mobile Convention Centre on 2 July 2012.
[src:flameout/airbus] The plans include a $600 million factory at the Mobile Aeroplex at Brookley for the assembly of the A220, A319, A320 and A321 aircraft.
[src:flameout/airbus] It could employ up to 1,000 full-time workers when operational.
[src:flameout/airbus] Construction began on 8 April 2013, and became operable by 2015, producing up to 50 aircraft per year by 2017.
[src:flameout/airbus] On 16 December 2024, it was reported that Airbus had leased 650,000 sq ft of office space in Bengaluru's Whitefield to build its Global Capacity Centre.
[src:flameout/airbus] The lease is for 10 years and valued at Rs 500 crore, securing the entire building in Titanium Tech Park.
[src:flameout/airbus] In this way, Airbus intends to strengthen its position in India.
[src:flameout/airbus] In October 2005 the British Ministry of Defence warned European politicians to stop, as it saw it, interfering in the corporate governance of EADS.
[src:flameout/airbus] The former UK Defence Procurement Minister Lord Drayson hinted that the UK government, a major customer for EADS, may withhold future contracts.
[src:flameout/airbus] On 4 April 2006, DaimlerChrysler announced its intention to reduce its shareholding from 30% to 22.5%.
[src:flameout/airbus] The company placed a value on the stake at "approximately €2.0 billion." Lagardère was to reduce its holding by an identical amount.
[src:flameout/airbus] However, Caisse des Dépôts et Consignations, a unit of the French government, acquired 2.25% of EADS.
[src:flameout/airbus] At issue, as a result, is the fact that the German and French shareholdings were now in imbalance.
[src:flameout/airbus] On 30 August 2006, shortly after the stock price decline caused by the A380 delivery delays, more than 5% of EADS stock was reportedly purchased by the Russian state-owned Vneshtorgbank, bringing its share to nearly 6%.
[src:flameout/airbus] In December 2007, Vneshtorgbank sold EADS shares to another state-controlled bank, Vnesheconombank.
[src:flameout/airbus] EADS shares were to be delivered by Vneshekonombank to the charter capital of JSC United Aircraft Corporation in 2008.
[src:flameout/airbus] On 3 October 2006, shortly after EADS admitted further delays in the Airbus 380 programme would cost the company 4.8 billion euros in lost earnings in 2010, EADS shares, traded on the Paris arm of Euronext, were suspended after they surpassed the 10% loss limit.
[src:flameout/airbus] Trading resumed later in the day with the one-day loss holding at 7%.
[src:flameout/airbus] In 2007, Dubai Holding acquired 3.12% of EADS stock, making the Dubai buy-out fund one of the largest institutional shareholders.
[src:flameout/airbus] In 2008, EADS had arms sales equivalent to $17.9 billion, which constituted 28% of total revenue.
[src:flameout/airbus] In April 2013, Daimler sold its shares in EADS.
[src:flameout/airbus] As of 31 December 2024, 73.7% of Airbus Group stock is publicly traded on six European stock exchanges (Euronext Paris in France, the Frankfurt Stock Exchange in Germany, and the four regional stock exchanges Bolsa de Madrid, Borsa de Barcelona, Bolsa de Valencia and Bolsa de Bilbao in Spain).
[src:flameout/airbus] 0.6% of the shares are treasury shares owned by Airbus, while the remaining 25.7% are owned by a "Contractual Partnership".
[src:flameout/airbus] SOGEPA is owned by the French State, GZBV is majority owned by the German state-owned investment and development bank KfW, and SEPI is a Spanish state holding company.
[src:flameout/airbus] In April 2020, Airbus announced that it had cut aircraft production by a third due to the COVID-19 outbreak.
[src:flameout/airbus] According to Guillaume Faury, the company was "bleeding cash at an unprecedented speed".
[src:flameout/airbus] The recession put its survival at stake and presented the need for deep job cuts throughout all Airbus departments.
[src:flameout/airbus] 3,000 workers in France were involved in government-assisted furlough schemes.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus has committed to "Flightpath 2050", an aviation industry plan to reduce noise, CO2, and NOx emissions.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus was the first aerospace business to become ISO 14001 certified, in January 2007; this is a broader certification covering the whole organisation, not just the aircraft it produces.
[src:flameout/airbus] In association with Honeywell and JetBlue, Airbus has developed an aviation biofuel to reduce pollution and dependence on fossil fuels, claiming that this has the potential to replace up to a third of the world's aviation fuel.
[src:flameout/airbus] Algae-based biofuel absorbs carbon dioxide during growth and does not compete with food production.
[src:flameout/airbus] This alternative may be commercially available by 2030 but algae and other vegetation-based fuels are in an early stage of development, and fuel-bearing algae have been expensive to develop.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus offers delivery flights to airlines using a 10% biofuel blend in standard engines.
[src:flameout/airbus] The fuel does not cut carbon emissions but is free of sulphur emissions, which demonstrates that the fuel could be used in commercial flights in unmodified engines.
[src:flameout/airbus] In September 2020, Airbus unveiled three liquid hydrogen-fueled "ZEROe" concept aircraft that it claims could become the first commercial zero-emission aircraft, entering service by 2035.
[src:flameout/airbus] The design includes an aircraft with six eight-bladed removable motors.
[src:flameout/airbus] At the Airbus Summit in March 2025, Airbus delivered updates on its development of the ZEROe hydrogen powered aircraft.
[src:flameout/airbus] Boeing has continually protested over "launch aid" and other forms of government aid to Airbus, while Airbus has argued that Boeing receives illegal subsidies through military and research contracts and tax breaks.
[src:flameout/airbus] In July 2004, former Boeing CEO Harry Stonecipher accused Airbus of abusing a 1992 bilateral EU-US agreement providing for disciplines for large civil aircraft support from governments.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus is given reimbursable launch investment (RLI), called "launch aid" by the US, from European governments, with the money being paid back with interest plus indefinite royalties, but only if the aircraft is a commercial success.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus contends that this system is fully compliant with the 1992 agreement and WTO rules.
[src:flameout/airbus] The agreement allows up to 33% of the programme cost to be met through government loans, which are to be fully repaid within 17 years with interest and royalties.
[src:flameout/airbus] These loans are held at a minimum interest rate equal to the cost of government borrowing plus 0.25%, which would be below market rates available to Airbus without government support.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus claims that since the signature of the EU-US agreement in 1992, it has repaid European governments more than US$6.7 billion and that this is 40% more than it has received.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus argues that the military contracts awarded to Boeing, the second largest US defence contractor, are in effect a form of subsidy, such as the controversy surrounding the Boeing KC-767 military contracting arrangements.
[src:flameout/airbus] The significant US government support of technology development via NASA also provides significant support to Boeing, as do the large tax breaks offered to Boeing, which some people claim are in violation of the 1992 agreement and WTO rules.
[src:flameout/airbus] In its recent products such as the 787, Boeing has also been offered direct financial support from local and state governments.
[src:flameout/airbus] In January 2005 the European Union and United States trade representatives, Peter Mandelson and Robert Zoellick respectively, agreed to talks aimed at resolving the increasing tensions.
[src:flameout/airbus] These talks were not successful with the dispute becoming more acrimonious rather than approaching a settlement.
[src:flameout/airbus] WTO ruled in August 2010 and in May 2011 that Airbus had received improper government subsidies through loans with below market rates from several European countries.
[src:flameout/airbus] In a separate ruling in February 2011, WTO found that Boeing had received local and federal aid in violation of WTO rules.
[src:flameout/airbus] In 2005 the Government Pension Fund of Norway recommended the exclusion of several companies producing cluster bombs or components.
[src:flameout/airbus] EADS and its sister company EADS Finance BV were among them, arguing that EADS manufactures "key components for cluster bombs".
[src:flameout/airbus] The criticism was centred around TDA, a joint venture between EADS and Thales S.A.
[src:flameout/airbus] TDA produced the mortar ammunition PR Cargo, which can be considered cluster ammunition, however this definition has since been successfully battled by EADS.
[src:flameout/airbus] EADS and its subsidiaries are now regarded as fulfilling all the conditions of the Ottawa Treaty.
[src:flameout/airbus] According to the new point of view, no product of EADS or its subsidiaries falls into the category of antipersonnel mines as defined by the Ottawa Treaty ("landmines under the Ottawa Treaty").
[src:flameout/airbus] In April 2006, the fund declared that the basis for excluding EADS from investments related to the production of cluster munitions is no longer valid, however its shareholding of MBDA means the fund still excludes EADS due to its indirect involvement in nuclear weapons production.
[src:flameout/airbus] On 2 June 2006 co-CEO Noël Forgeard and Airbus CEO Gustav Humbert resigned following the controversy caused by the June 2006 announcement that deliveries of the A380 would be delayed by a further six months.
[src:flameout/airbus] Forgeard was one of a number of executives including Jean-Paul Gut who exercised stock options in November 2005 and March 2006.
[src:flameout/airbus] He and twenty-one other executives are under investigation as to whether they knew about the delays in the Airbus A380 project which caused a 26% fall in EADS shares when publicised.
[src:flameout/airbus] The French government's actions were also under investigation; The state-owned bank Caisse des Dépots et Consignations (CDC) bought part of Lagardère's 7.5% stake in EADS in April 2006, allowing that latter to partially escape the June 2006 losses.
[src:flameout/airbus] In September 2024, Airbus received negative press attention for its links with Aviation Industry Corporation of China (AVIC), a Chinese company that provides aircraft to the Myanmar junta.
[src:flameout/airbus] In a joint report, NGOs Justice for Myanmar and Info Birmanie outlined how the supplied aircraft and weapons were used by the Myanmar military to commit war crimes in the Myanmar civil war.
[src:flameout/airbus] The report called on Airbus to use its influence to pressure the Chinese firm to end its arms sales to the Myanmar junta.
[src:flameout/airbus] In response to the report, Airbus stated its collaboration focused exclusively on the civil domain, and that its conduct complied with all laws and regulations.
[src:flameout/airbus] In June 2025, Justice for Myanmar reported that Airbus had completed its divestment from AviChina, AVIC's publicly listed subsidiary, by 1 April 2025.
[src:flameout/airbus] In 2003 Tony Yengeni, former chief whip of South Africa's African National Congress, was convicted of fraud worth around US$5 billion relating to an arms deal with South Africa, in which Airbus (formerly EADS) were major players.
[src:flameout/airbus] It was claimed that Airbus had admitted that it had "rendered assistance" to around thirty senior officials, including defence force chief General Siphiwe Nyanda, to obtain luxury vehicles.
[src:flameout/airbus] In March 2003, South Africa withdrew all charges of bribery against the former head of EADS South Africa, and in September 2004, the prosecutor's office dismissed the bribery charges against Yengeni.
[src:flameout/airbus] In August 2012 the UK's Serious Fraud Office opened a criminal investigation into an EADS subsidiary, GPT Special Project Management Ltd, regarding bribery allegations made by GPT's former programme director, Ian Foxley.
[src:flameout/airbus] Foxley alleged that luxury cars were bought for senior Saudis, and that millions of pounds sterling were paid to mysterious Cayman Islands companies, possibly to secure a £2 billion contract to renew the Saudi Arabian National Guard's military telecommunications network.
[src:flameout/airbus] Foxley's allegations were supported by two other GPT employees.
[src:flameout/airbus] The later agreement between Airbus and the SFO on 31 January 2020 excluded the settlement of this case.
[src:flameout/airbus] In July 2016, SFO opened a criminal investigation into "suspicions of fraud, bribes and corruption" after Airbus informed British authorities of a failure to disclose the role played by some intermediaries facilitating the sale of aircraft.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus was required to provide this information in order to benefit from export credits, which the British, French and German governments had suspended.
[src:flameout/airbus] In March 2017, the PNF subsequently opened a preliminary investigation into "suspicions of fraud and corruption in civil aviation activities" in cooperation with the SFO.
[src:flameout/airbus] The allegations included that from 2012 onwards Airbus was responsible for recruiting and remunerating intermediaries to influence the award of civil and military contracts.
[src:flameout/airbus] Payments worth hundreds of millions of euros in alleged secret commissions were made and numerous sales including in Saudi Arabia, Kazakhstan, Philippines, Indonesia, Austria, China and Mauritius were under suspicion of bribery.
[src:flameout/airbus] The investigation focused on the Airbus, Strategy and Marketing Organization (SMO), the department responsible for negotiating sales contracts and which, La Tribune reported as having "a network and an incredible influence around the world".
[src:flameout/airbus] Directed successively by Jean-Paul Gut and Marwan Lahoud, the SMO was dissolved in 2016 under the new executive director, Thomas Enders, as part of a "clean hands" operation.
[src:flameout/airbus] In 2014, in a case referred to as the Kazakhgate affair, a search at Airbus Helicopters by French authorities found emails confirming that Airbus had agreed in principle to pay €12 million in bribes to the Prime Minister of Kazakhstan to facilitate the sale of helicopters.
[src:flameout/airbus] Officers from the Central Anti-Corruption Office (OCLCIFF) then searched the home of Marwan Lahoud on 8 February 2016.
[src:flameout/airbus] This revealed that two Turkish intermediaries had claimed payment of commissions due in connection with the sale of 160 aircraft to China valued at US$10 billion.
[src:flameout/airbus] A message by Lahoud suggested that the commissions could reach US$250 million.
[src:flameout/airbus] The SMO was to conceal these commissions as false invoices for a fictitious Caspian pipeline project.
[src:flameout/airbus] In January 2020, French, British and American courts validated three agreements between Airbus and the PNF, the UK SFO, and the US DoJ.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus recognised the charges and agreed to pay fines of €2.1 billion in France, €984 million in the United Kingdom and €526 million in the United States.
[src:flameout/airbus] The penalties were the highest ever issued by the French and British bodies.
[src:flameout/airbus] These settlements close the prosecution of Airbus regarding the Kazakhstan case but not allegations of misconduct in Saudi Arabia, China and Turkey, which Airbus denies.
[src:flameout/airbus] Airbus managers may still be pursued as private individuals.
[src:flameout/flameout] In aviation, a **flameout** (or **flame-out**) is the run-down of a jet engine or other turbine engine due to the extinguishment of the flame in its combustor.
[src:flameout/flameout] The loss of flame can have a variety of causes, such as fuel starvation, excessive altitude, compressor stall, foreign object damage deriving from birds, hail, or volcanic ash, severe precipitation, mechanical failure, or very low ambient temperatures.
[src:flameout/flameout] Early jet engines were prone to flameout following disturbances of inlet airflow, or sudden or inappropriate thrust lever movements, which resulted in incorrect air-fuel ratios in the combustion chamber.
[src:flameout/flameout] Modern engines are much more robust in this respect, and are often digitally controlled, which allows for significantly more effective control of all engine parameters to prevent flameouts and even initiate an automatic restart if a flameout occurs.
[src:flameout/flameout] Flameouts occur most frequently at intermediate or low power settings such as in cruise and descent.
[src:flameout/flameout] To prevent a flameout when atmospheric or operational conditions are conducive to it, engine control systems usually provide a continuous ignition function.
[src:flameout/flameout] Igniters are normally used only at engine start, until the flame in the combustion chamber becomes self-sustaining.
[src:flameout/flameout] With continuous ignition, instead, the igniters are continually sparked every second or less, so that if a flameout occurs, combustion can immediately be restored.
[src:flameout/flameout] Following a flameout, jet engines can normally be restarted in flight, provided the aircraft is flying within the portion of its flight envelope defined as the *engine relight envelope*.
[src:flameout/flameout] For example, the Airbus A320 passenger jet has a maximum ceiling of over 39,000 ft (12,000 m), but its certified engine relight envelope only extends to 30,000 ft (9,100 m).
[src:flameout/flameout] Up to that altitude, a windmill restart can be attempted at airspeeds greater than 260 knots (480 km/h; 300 mph); below that speed, a starter-assisted relight is required.
